properties.Title: Alberta Emergency Alert - Urban Fire Alert
properties.Summary:
Description: There is a fire in the King Edward Hotel in Pincher Creek. Fire Services are on scene. Main Street is closed between Hewetson Avenue and Bev McLachlin Drive. Due to fire hoses across the road avoid the Hewetson Avenue Bridge. For access to downtown use the east approach from Waterton Avenue/Highway 6.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Temperatures have dropped to around -40 with light winds giving wind chills near -50. The extreme cold is expected to moderate this afternoon. ### Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NTStorm.

properties.Title: Weather Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Winter Weather Travel Advisory in effect for today. Lake effect snow off Lake Superior is expected to continue today. Strong southwesterly wind gusts of 50 to 70 km/h will also result in blowing snow over exposed areas. Total snowfall amounts of 10 cm are possible by the time the snow weakens later this evening. Travel is expected to be hazardous today due to heavy snow and blowing snow resulting in reduced visibilities. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Summary:

Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. A frontal system will move through the interior today. Snow will continue today with substantial accumulations expected. Snow will taper off this evening and should end around midnight. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
